<br>
Folks, it's the artist's property.  They get to decide what they want if .. if .. IF .. they are willing to give you limited rights to use their property.  If they want to make you pay, and advertise, and attach a picture of your naked butt, and smooch a chimpanzee in heat on national television, all as a condition of using their property, that's their right.  Just as it's your right to decide the conditions are unreasonable, and you don't feel like doing that.  In which case, don't use their damn property.<br>
<br>
Your point of view can easily be reduced to the absurd.  Suppose they decide to charge $100.  You don't think $100 is reasonable, only $10 is reasonable.  Do you get to send them $10 and do as you please?  Of course not.  Just because they choose to make part of the price non-monetary, in the form of advertising, doesn't change the analysis one lick.  It's the artist's property, the artist can charge whatever it wants, and you can either pay it, or not, or negotiate.  But you can't just grab their work because you don't like the price or conditions.   <br>
<br>
I also find it very interesting, Ninen, that your &quot;take&quot; is that you'd feel entitled to grab the artist's work and mangle it whether or not it's right, or legal.  Perhaps there's some basis for TWC's rep as baby-killers after all.  <br>
<br>
